This paper is likely to belong to the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category as it deals with the task of offensive tweet detection, which is a natural language processing problem. Additionally, the use of recurrent neural networks (RNNs) such as LSTMs and GRUs is a common technique in NLP. 

The paper also involves pre-processing techniques, which could fall under the Information Retrieval (cs.IR) sub-category. 

The use of deep learning models and the investigation of model complexity could also place this paper in the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category. 

The investigation of multiple architectures and the use of convolutional layers could suggest the Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) sub-category, but this is less likely given the focus on text data. 

Finally, the investigation of different pre-processing techniques and the use of RNNs could also suggest the Cybersecurity (cs.CY) sub-category, as these techniques are commonly used in the detection of malicious or offensive content online.
